Mrs McCourt, who is originally from Oxfordshire in the UK, said: 'He [the doorman] was trying desperately to hail a cab and a lady walked out five meters in front of him and hailed a cab and got into it.

'And I went ''that's my cab, I want that cab!'''

With the baby's head already crowning, Mrs McCourt gave up trying to get to nearby Lenox Hill Hospital and sat down on the sidewalk. 

With doorman Mr Rudovic supporting her back and female bystanders holding the baby's head, the newborn arrived in under five minutes. People rushed to give their scarves and coats to wrap the baby as the temperature was in the chilly mid-30s.

Mrs McCourt's husband Cian McCourt, 40, who was stuck in traffic, told MailOnline today that he feared the worst when he came running up and saw his wife on the ground.

Mr McCourt, a partner at A&L Goodbody law firm, said: 'It was a complete shock. I came running up the street and I immediately knew it was my wife.

'I saw the crowd and I feared the worst, that she had been knocked down or something - it was really emotional.

